RABIES, SUMMARY: WEEK OF 3 MAY 1998
***********************************
A ProMED-mail post
Date: Fri, 08 May 1998 13:16:25 -0400
From: Dorothy Preslar <dpreslar@fas.org>
Source: News media

(1) Indonesia
Jakarta Post, 8 May - Livestock authorities on the eastern island of Flores
have announced a plan to slaughter as many as 170 thousand dogs to contain a
rabies outbreak that has caused eight human deaths.
(2) USA - Tennessee
Calgary (Canada) Herald, 7 May - A horse, suspected of rabies, has been shot
to death after the animal attacked and killed a farmer in Nolensville, TN
(30 km southeast of Nashville). The horse's owner sustained 22 rib fractures
and hoof and bite marks on his upper torso and face. He died of internal
bleeding. When a rescue team arrived, the horse attacked a car into which a
volunteer firefighter had gone for safety after being menaced by the horse.
(3) USA - North Carolina
Chapel Hill Herald, 1 May - The confirmation of rabies in four raccoons has
brought the total number of cases (since the first case was recorded in July
1996) to 146 in Orange County, NC. The raccoons attacked dogs, three of
which were vaccinated and one of which was not and had to be destroyed.
(4) USA - California
City News Service of Los Angeles, 5 May - Three more rabid bats have been
found within the last week in Los Angeles County. In two cases, children had
played with the sick bats and had to undergo preventive treatment.
--
